
[1]brook

   BROOK, n. [Gr. to rain, to pour, to flow.] A small natural stream of
   water, or a current flowing from a spring or fountain less than a
   river. In some parts of America, run is used in a like sense; but run
   is also applied to larger streams than brook.

   BROOK, v.t. [Gr. to eat, to grind the teeth.] Literally, to chew or
   digest, as the Fr. digerir. Hence,

   To bear; to endure; to support; as,young men cannot brook restraint.
